ch.%20Even%20lentils%20are%20tempered%20with%20the%20same%20four%20ingredients%20because%20any%20other%20tempering%20often%20turns%20the%20lentils%20into%20%26quot%3Bhospital-type%20dal%26quot%3B.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EEverything%20Tastes%20The%20Same%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI'm%20quite%20sure%20that%20half%20the%20market%20for%20Eno%20or%20Digene%20in%20India%20can%20be%20credited%20to%20this%20mother%20sauce%20because%20our%20stomachs%20have%20literally%20become%20allergic%20to%20it.%20We%20eat%20it%20day%20in%20and%20day%20out.%20We%20even%20put%20it%20in%20our%20eggs%20in%20the%20morning.%20That%20famous%20street%20side%20dish%2C%20'anda%20ghotala'%2C%20is%20also%20a%20variant%20of%20this%20concoction%2C%20blended%20with%20boiled%20eggs%20and%20served%20with%20fried%20eggs%20on%20top.%20%26quot%3BGhotala%26quot%3B%20literally%20translates%20to%20scam%2C%20and%20such%20dishes%20indeed%20are%20a%20scam%20-%20and%20products%20of%20sheer%20lack%20of%20imagination.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThere's%20something%20to%20be%20said%20here%20about%20the%20snob%20of%20all%20cuisines%20-%20French%20food.%20At%20least%20the%20French%20tend%20to%20glorify%20every%20ingredient%20using%20sauces%20made%20with%20completely%20different%20flavour%20compositions.%20So%20a%20%3Cem%3Ebeurre%20blanc%3C%2Fem%3E%20(literally%20translates%20to%20white%20butter)%20is%20a%20simple%20butter%20sauce%20emulsified%20with%20vinegar%20and%20wine%2C%20and%20boiled%20with%20shallots.%20In%20fact%2C%20each%20of%20the%20mother%20sauces%20of%20French%20cuisine%20%E2%80%94%20%3Cem%3EB%C3%A9chamel%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%3Cem%3EVelout%C3%A9%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%3Cem%3EEspagnole%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%3Cem%3EHollandaise%20%3C%2Fem%3Eand%20%3Cem%3ESauce%20Tomat%3C%2Fem%3E%20(Tomato)%20%E2%80%94%20is%20defined%20by%20a%20distinct%20profile%20that%20goes%20with%20various%20proteins%20and%20carbs.%20While%20%3Cem%3Eb%C3%A9chamel's%20%3C%2Fem%3Emain%20star%20is%20milk%2C%20%3Cem%3Evelout%C3%A9's%20%3C%2Fem%3Estar%20ingredient%20is%20chicken%20stock%20thickened%20with%20a%20%3Cem%3Eroux%20%3C%2Fem%3E(all-purpose%20flour%20that's%20cooked%20with%20butter).%20Similarly%2C%20%3Cem%3Evelout%C3%A9%20%3C%2Fem%3Euses%20beef%20stock%20with%20brown%20%3Cem%3Eroux%3C%2Fem%3E.%20%3Cem%3EHollandaise%20%3C%2Fem%3Euses%20raw%20eggs%20with%20lemon%20juice%20to%20create%20an%20absolutely%20divine%2C%20velvety%20texture%20and%20refreshing%20flavour%2C%20while%20%3Cem%3ESauce%20Tomat%20%3C%2Fem%3Eclearly%20is%20an%20ode%20to%20tomatoes%2C%20which%20are%20cooked%20with%20herbs%20and%20reduced%20to%20a%20delectable%20thick%20consistency.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20derivatives%20of%20these%20sauces%20with%20multiple%20other%20ingredients%20run%20into%20hundreds%20of%20other%20variants%2C%20each%20distinct%20from%20the%20other.%20For%20example%2C%20sauce%20%3Cem%3ECharcuti%C3%A8re%20%3C%2Fem%3Euses%20the%20mother%20sauce%20%3Cem%3Eespagnole%20%3C%2Fem%3Ewith%20dry%20mustard%20and%20onions.%20Sauce%20Mornay%20uses%20the%20mother%20sauce%20%3Cem%3Eb%C3%A9chamel%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20with%20onions%2C%20cloves%2C%20Gruy%C3%A8re%20cheese%20and%20Parmesan.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3ERescuing%20Indian%20Cuisine%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt's%20not%20that%20Indian%20cuisine%20was%20always%20so%20monotonous.%20Not%20in%20the%20least%20bit.%20It%20still%20isn't.%20Only%2C%20it's%20the%20on-the-go%20cooking%20(the%20%26quot%3Bscammy%26quot%3B%20type)%20that%20has%20made%20this%20onion-tomato-ginger-garlic%20concoction%20the%20mainstay%20of%20all%20%26quot%3Bdishes%26quot%3B.%20%C2%A0Things%20were%20not%20supposed%20to%20be%20like%20this.%20The%20original%20urad%20dal%2C%20also%20known%20as%20'kali%20dal'%20and%20which%20is%20now%20served%20as%20'makhani%20dal'%2C%20was%20always%20slow-cooked%20to%20perfection%20with%20only%20caramelised%20onions%20added%20for%20tempering.%20The%20famous%20'junglee%20maas'%20of%20Rajasthan%20was%20a%20glorification%20of%20the%20mighty%20Mathania%20chillies%20grown%20locally%20in%20Jodhpur%20to%20elevate%20game%20meat%20hunted%20by%20the%20royals%20of%20yesteryears.%20The%20only%20other%20ingredients%20in%20this%20dish%20were%20ghee%20and%20garlic%20to%20remove%20the%20gamey%20smell%20of%20meat.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20the%20opulent%20biryani%20did%20not%20look%20anything%20like%20it%20does%20today%3A%20layers%20of%20red-curried%20meat%20or%20chicken%2C%20again%20with%20the%20same%20mother%20sauce%2C%20served%20with%20white%20rice.%20There%20are%20two%20origin%20stories%20of%20biryani%2C%20and%20neither%20of%20them%20mentions%20the%20meats%20cooked%20to%20a%20curry%20with%20tomatoes%2C%20onions%20and%20ginger%20garlic.%20The%20'Birian'%20that%20came%20via%20Persian%20(much%20before%20the%20Mughals)%20traders%20was%20simply%20a%20one-pot%20dish%20made%20with%20rice%2C%20meat%20and%20spices%2C%20cooked%20underground%20in%20an%20earthen%20pot%20in%20a%20coal-lined%20pit.%20This%20spice-infused%20rice%20later%20became%20'Biryani'%20in%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20other%20story%20of%20Biryani%20has%20its%20origins%20surprisingly%20in%20Sangam%20literature%2C%20which%20speaks%20of%20a%20dish%20called%20'oonchoru'%20dating%20back%20to%20200%20BCE-200%20CE.%20This%20dish%20of%20Chera%20Kings%20was%20made%20with%20rice%2C%20ghee%2C%20meat%2C%20turmeric%2C%20pepper%2C%20coriander%20and%20bay%20leaf.%20Even%20if%20we%20were%20to%20look%20at%20the%20Mughals%20for%20Biryani%2C%20the%20only%20recipe%20mentioned%20in%20Mughal%20texts%20is%20from%20the%20time%20of%20Bahadur%20Shah%20Zafar%2C%20which%20again%20spoke%20of%20rice%20infused%20with%20spices%2C%20with%20no%20mention%20of%20layering.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3ENortheast%20Stands%20Out%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhy%20the%20mother%20sauce%20of%20India%20has%20peeved%20me%20so%20much%20is%20because%20the%20spectrum%20of%20flavours%20remains%20almost%20identical.%20The%20sauce%20becomes%20%3Cem%3Epav%20bhaaji%3C%2Fem%3E%20with%20the%20addition%20of%20vegetables%2C%20but%20it%20also%20doubles%20up%20as%20%3Cem%3Ekadhai%20chicken%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%3Cem%3Eshahi%20paneer%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20and%20%3Cem%3Ebutter%20chicken%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20depending%20on%20what%20you%20add%20to%20it.%20They%20all%20are%2C%20at%20the%20core%2C%20just%20the%20same.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20only%20region%20in%20India%20that%20looks%20beyond%20this%20style%20of%20cooking%20is%20the%20Northeast%20-%20and%20Southern%20India%20to%20some%20extent.%20In%20the%20former%2C%20we%20find%20a%20good%20degree%20of%20experimentation%20with%20ingredients%2C%20and%20fermentation%20processes%20are%20used%20to%20create%20umami%20flavours.%20Like%20the%20Iromba%20of%20Manipur%2C%20in%20which%20fish%20is%20fermented%20and%20then%20flavoured%20with%20fresh%20bay%20leaves%2C%20onion%2C%20cumin%2C%20chillies%2C%20and%20chives%2C%20or%20a%20Mui%20Borok%20of%20Tripura%2C%20in%20which%20the%20stars%20of%20the%20curry%20are%20local%20herbs%2C%20bamboo%20and%20vegetables%20with%20just%20fish%20stock%20used%20as%20the%20base.%20But%20then%20again%2C%20Assam's%20Fish%20Tenga%2C%20or%20even%20the%20popular%20Thukpa%20from%20Tibet%20that's%20eaten%20in%20Sikkim%20and%20Darjeeling%2C%20go%20back%20to%20the%20same%20four%20ingredients.%20In%20the%20South%20too%2C%20nothing%20can%20escape%20the%20'Big%20Four'%2C%20though%20one%20does%20find%20dishes%20like%20the%20yoghurt-based%20Moru%20curry%20occasionally.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20think%20we%20Indians%20clearly%20need%20to%20put%20our%20foot%20down%20and%20say%20%26quot%3Benough%20is%20enough%26quot%3B%20to%20this%20all-pervasive%20'mother%20sauce'.%20We%20must%20try%20going%20back%20to%20our%20roots%2C%20where%20monotony%20was%20never%20the%20norm.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E(Zainab%20Sikander%20is%20a%20political%20analyst%20and%20columnist%20covering%20Indian%20politics%20since%20the%20last%20decade.%20She's%20an%20avid%20traveller%20and%20a%20bona-fide%20foodie.)%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EDisclaimer%3A%20Th